Dawn

Target IP: 192.168.246.11

Scanning


There are four TCP ports open on the target machine: HTTP, SMB, and MySQL. I will begin my enumeration with the HTTP application on port 80.

Enumeration

Port 80: HTTP

The webpage above is displayed when we visit this port using a web-browser. Doing a source-code review did not show anything important either.


The nikto scan above mentions there is a directory called /logs/.


Doing a directory search highlights two directories: /logs/ and /cctv/; however, I did not have access to the second directory!

This directory /logs/ contains four files; the first three are zero in size due to forbidden access. However, the management.log is interesting as it contains information. The output of this file looks like it is from pspy as we can see what processes are being run at the moment.

Ports 139 and 445: SMB

There is an interesting share called ITDEPT. As a guest, we have READ and WRITE permissions over this share; meaning we can upload and download files! There are no files to download from this share; however, the upload looks quite neat! Maybe this ITDEPT shows up in the management.log we obtained from the /logs/ directory?

Exploitation


When taking a closer look at the management.log, I noticed there are two main cronjob scripts that gets executed from the ITDEPT share I found in SMB. They are web-control and product-control scripts. What if I create a script with a reverse shell inside it? Will the host execute it?


I created two scripts with the same bash reverse shell with two different ports: product-control at 80 and web-control at 445. The contents of the scripts are shown above. Then I started listeners on both ports.


I uploaded both of the scripts to the SMB share called ITDEPT.


After uploading the scripts, I got an immediate reverse connection on both shells! The first shell above I got a connection back as dawn. I will use this shell! Now we have a foothold on the machine as dawn.

Privilege Escalation


Running sudo -l shows we can run /usr/bin/mysql as root! However, trying to elevate the privileges using this binary did not work.


I did find /usr/bin/zsh binary to elevate privileges.


And now I have a root shell!
